### Patients

The participants in the trial were patients aged 18 years or older. Men and women were enrolled, although women of child-bearing potential were excluded from the study. To be eligible for the study, patients were required to have stage 1 hypertension: systolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} between 140 and 159 mm Hg, or diastolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} between 90 and 99 mm Hg, or both. Patients could either be untreated at the time of study entry, or have stage 1 hypertension while on current monotherapy. This latter group was termed the treated but uncontrolled group, and probably included patients who originally had stage 2 or higher types of hypertension before starting treatment. Patients on centrally acting α-agonists such as clonidine were not eligible for study entry unless they discontinued that treatment at least 4 weeks before entering the protocol. Because this was a practice-based trial, physicians were instructed to use their judgment as far as including patients with concomitant conditions, and to ensure that patients were not exposed to any deleterious consequences by virtue of following the protocol. If at any time during the study a patient's systolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} was ≥180 mm Hg, or the diastolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} was ≥110 mm Hg, they were to be withdrawn from the trial and given appropriate therapy to bring their {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} under control.
